<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">Actually, the way I laid it out above is real.  I didn't go into great detail but it's close.  There is NOT an even split of xp unless everyone is same level, race modifier and class modifier.<p>

<br>
Level 30 Ogre warrior:  <br>
 Ogre      115<br>
 Warrior     9<br>
 Level 30    1.1<br>
Total XP at base:        30739500<br>
Total XP at next level:  46250527<br>
One bubble of xp is about 635510 points.<p>

Level 30 Troll SK:<br>
 Troll     120<br>
 SK         14<br>
 Level 30    1.1<br>
Total XP at base:        49896000<br>
Total XP at next level:  55053768<br>
One bubble of xp is about 1031553 points.<p>

Level 30 HE Cleric:<br>
 High Elf   100<br>
 Cleric      10<br>
 Level 30     1.1<br>
Total XP at base:       29700000<br>
Total XP at next level: 32770100<br>
One bubble is about 614020 points.<p>

Level 30 Halfling Rogue:<br>
  Halfling  95<br>
  Warrior    9.05<br>
  Level 30   1.1<br>
Total XP at base:        25534575<br>
Total XP at next level:  28174093<br>
Each bubble is equal to: 527903 points.<br>
Put these people into a group, how much XP would each get from a pool of 100,000 points?<br>
     Ogre gets 22624 points.<br>
     Troll gets 36723 points.<br>
     HE gets 21859 points.<br>
     Halfling gets 18793 points.<br>
If we compare this to the bubbles that we see filling up, we would see that they get the same amount of bubble filled.  In this case 3.5% of the bubble.<br>
If the grouped earned like a 1,000,000 points, you would see everyone earn a third of a bubble experience.  The appearance is that everyone is getting the same amount of XP because everyone's bubbles fill up the same but in actuality, the percentage of XP is the same, not the numbers being earned.</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
